{"id":"1605.08589","submitter":"Dmitri Vassiliev","authors":"Yan-Long Fang, Michael Levitin, Dmitri Vassiliev","title":"Spectral analysis of the Dirac operator on a 3-sphere","comments":"Slightly extended text with updated bibliography","journal-ref":"Operators and Matrices, 2018, vol. 12, p. 501-527","doi":"10.7153/oam-2018-12-31","report-no":null,"categories":"math.SP gr-qc math-ph math.DG math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the (massless) Dirac operator on a 3-sphere equipped with Riemannian\nmetric. For the standard metric the spectrum is known. In particular, the\neigenvalues closest to zero are the two double eigenvalues +3/2 and -3/2. Our\naim is to analyse the behaviour of eigenvalues when the metric is perturbed in\nan arbitrary smooth fashion from the standard one. We derive explicit\nperturbation formulae for the two eigenvalues closest to zero, taking account\nof the second variations. Note that these eigenvalues remain double eigenvalues\nunder perturbations of the metric: they cannot split because of a particular\nsymmetry of the Dirac operator in dimension three (it commutes with the\nantilinear operator of charge conjugation). Our perturbation formulae show that\nin the first approximation our two eigenvalues maintain symmetry about zero and\nare completely determined by the increment of Riemannian volume. Spectral\nasymmetry is observed only in the second approximation of the perturbation\nprocess. As an example we consider a special family of metrics, the so-called\ngeneralized Berger spheres, for which the eigenvalues can be evaluated\nexplicitly.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 May 2016 11:34:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 2 May 2017 11:24:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-10"}
